               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary>
                     <p>This small, palm leaf manuscript contains the complete text of the <title xml:lang="sa">Brahmasūtra</title>, in Nandināgarī script. Each <term xml:lang="sa">sūtra</term> is preceded and followed by <quote xml:lang="sa">oṃ</quote>. Although the title folio reads <title xml:lang="sa">Sūtrabhāṣya</title>, the <term xml:lang="sa">sūtra</term>s are presented without commentary.</p>
<p>The <title xml:lang="sa">Brahmasūtra</title> is usually attributed to <persName xml:lang="sa">Bādarāyaṇa</persName>, who is sometimes called <persName xml:lang="sa">Vyāsa</persName>. In the final rubric of this manuscript, the text is attributed to <persName xml:lang="sa">Kṛṣṇadvaipāyana</persName>, the traditional author of the <title xml:lang="sa">Mahābhārata</title>, who is also known as <persName xml:lang="sa">Vyāsa</persName>.</p>
                  </summary>
                  
